"cultural_note": {
  "title": "Languages and Regional Identity in Italy",
  "content": [
    "Italy has a rich linguistic diversity. Besides standard Italian, many regions have their own dialects or even distinct languages.",
    "Examples: Sicilian in Sicily, Sardinian in Sardinia, and Friulian in Friuli are recognized as minority languages.",
    "In some northern regions like Trentino-Alto Adige, both Italian and German are official languages.",
    "Italians are generally proud of their regional identity and may speak dialect at home while using standard Italian in formal settings.",
    "When meeting Italians abroad, they often identify by their city or region first ('Sono di Napoli', 'Sono romano') rather than just saying 'Sono italiano'.",
    "Many Italians are multilingual, especially in border regions. French is spoken near France, Slovenian near Slovenia, and German in South Tyrol."
  ]
},

